## Query Optimisation

### Analysis

- Run `EXPLAIN (ANALYZE, BUFFERS)` before optimising slow queries
- Inspect sequential scans, index usage, and buffer hits

### Projections and Pagination

- Select only needed columns; avoid `SELECT *`
- Use cursor-based pagination (`WHERE id < last_seen`) for large datasets instead of `OFFSET`
- Use `LIMIT` with sensible bounds

### Batch Operations

- Prefer bulk inserts over row-by-row
- Use `INSERT ... ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING/UPDATE` for upserts
- Use `bulkWrite` in MongoDB for multiple updates

### CTEs and Compiled Queries

- Use CTEs for readability and to avoid repeated subqueries
- Use prepared statements when the same query runs repeatedly with different parameters

```sql
WITH updated AS (UPDATE posts SET status = 'archived' WHERE author_id = $1 RETURNING id)
SELECT COUNT(*) FROM updated;
```

---

## Database Security

### Injection Prevention

- Use parameterised queries or ORM methods for all database access; never concatenate user input into SQL
- Validate and sanitise input at the boundary

### Row-Level Security (RLS)

- Enable RLS on tables with multi-tenant or per-user access
- Define policies per operation (SELECT, INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE)
- Use `current_setting` or session variables for user context

### Sensitive Data

- Encrypt sensitive columns at rest (e.g. SSN, payment data)
- Use application-level encryption or database extensions (e.g. `pgcrypto`)

### Audit Logging

- Log schema changes, sensitive data access, and bulk operations
- Store `table_name`, `record_id`, `action`, `old_values`, `new_values`, `changed_by`, `changed_at`

---

## Migration Directives

### Versioning

- Use sequential, versioned migration files (e.g. `001_create_users.sql`, `002_add_roles.sql`)
- Maintain a `schema_version` table for applied migrations

### Transactional Migrations

- Wrap migrations in transactions where possible
- Document rollback steps for each migration
- Test rollback in staging before production

```sql
BEGIN;
ALTER TABLE users ADD COLUMN role VARCHAR(50) DEFAULT 'user';
COMMIT;
```

---

## Backup and Recovery Directives

### Automated Backups

- Schedule automated backups (e.g. daily full, hourly incremental)
- Store backups off-host and in a separate region

### Point-in-Time Recovery

- Enable WAL archiving for point-in-time recovery where supported

### Retention Policy

- Define retention policy (e.g. 7 days daily, 4 weeks weekly)
- Test restore procedures regularly

---

## Checklist

- [ ] Schema normalised to 3NF unless denormalisation is justified
- [ ] Indexes on foreign keys and frequently filtered/sorted columns
- [ ] Constraints enforce domain rules (NOT NULL, CHECK, UNIQUE)
- [ ] Parameterised queries for all user input
- [ ] RLS enabled for multi-tenant or per-user access
- [ ] Migrations versioned and transactional
- [ ] Backup and retention policy defined and tested
